1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:15,000
It is the 27th of June 2016 today and we are here in Los Angeles, California.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:22,000
This is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech and working with the Civil Rights History Project

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:29,000
of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:36,000
We have with us John Bishop of Media Generation behind the camera also Guha Shankar of the Library of Congress is here with us.

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:41,000
And we are so honored to be here with Norma Tume.

7
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:51,000
And if I could ask you is the one time I will coach you at all to introduce yourself with a full sentence, my name is, or I am, and where you are born and what year?

8
00:00:51,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Okay, I am Norma M. Tume currently. I was born in 1949 in San Diego, California, Norma Stoker.

9
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:08,000
And later I married so my name was Norma Armore. At the time I was in the Black Panther Party my name was Norma Armore.

10
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:15,000
So I just, historical purposes for my children, my grandchildren, I wanted to make sure that those names were on file.

11
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Thank you.

12
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
And can you tell me about the adoption of M. Tume?

13
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Well, I married in M. Tume who changed his name in the 60s as a lot of us were doing. We didn't want our slave names anymore.

14
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:42,000
And so he chose M. Tume. His name is Omawali M. Tume and it means the sun returns. And it's Kiswahili and Nigerian.

15
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:43,000
It's powerful.

16
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Yeah.

17
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
So wonderful. And if you could tell, let's start with your childhood or even before your parents and tell me a little bit about your...

18
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:59,000
All right. My mother was Doris Sims. She was from born in Louisiana but raised in Arkansas and Louisiana.

19
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Came to California during the World War II, moved to the layhold where, you know, folks were going to where they could work in the war industry.

20
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:18,000
My dad was born in Longview, Texas. He went to the military and after he got out, he moved to San Diego. He became a librarian of all things.

21
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:28,000
And I lived in San Diego until I was about four. Then moved to Los Angeles with my mom, my folks split up.

22
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:37,000
So I've been in Los Angeles area most of my life. I moved away when I was in the party for a few years. I moved up North.

23
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:43,000
Came back home to Roost and pretty much been here since.

24
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Kisni, I wonder if you could tell me a little bit about the racial geography of Los Angeles during those years.

25
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,000
And if that shapes you at all.

26
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:03,000
It did. And I tell you my first experience, even thinking about me being in the skin really a lot.

27
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Where I lived in Los Angeles, it was primarily after Americans or Negroes or Colors or Blacks, as we became over the years.

28
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:20,000
And very few Latinos who were pretty much all Mexican.

29
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:29,000
One or two Asian, as you came further west, we had more Japanese, went further north, more Korean.

30
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:33,000
But where I lived, it was mainly Black people.

31
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Very poor neighborhood. I grew up in South Central around 21st and Naomi for those of you who know Los Angeles.

32
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And almost everybody came to school with cardboard and the shoes when they started wearing out.

33
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:57,000
I mean, it was no, you didn't think of yourself as super poor until you were able to get out of that environment and see what other people had.

34
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Because the other people around you, they pretty much had what you didn't have, what you didn't have, rather.

35
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:15,000
When I was in high school in the mid-60s, started to become a little bit more conscious about what's going on there, what's going on around the world.

36
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Some of our older brothers and neighbors and friends, and as we got to be seniors, some of our boyfriends were drafted, went to Vietnam.

37
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,000
I think that opened a lot of folks eyes.

38
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Especially when we saw the guys, the ones that made it back, they didn't come back quite the same.

39
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:38,000
And a lot of them have never been the same since then.

40
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Like I said, very poor. I managed to get a scholarship. $250.

41
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:52,000
From high school to go to college, you know, go figure. That would buy about book and a half these days.

42
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:58,000
So I went to Jefferson High School, which was basically all black.

43
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:07,000
We had two Caucasians, two brothers that I remember the Crab Whales, I remember because they only wasn't this whole school.

44
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,000
But that's kind of what the neighborhood was like. We were poor.

45
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:21,000
And then when riots started, when people started really, really feeling like enough is enough, we really don't have what we need to survive.

46
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:29,000
Folks got angry and they started doing what they thought they needed to do to get some attention.

47
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,000
What year did you graduate high school?

48
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:35,000
I graduated in 1967. In 1967.

49
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:44,000
Yeah, so it was just after we had the big watts uprising. After I graduated I went to Cal State LA.

50
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:49,000
And we had a very active black student union there.

51
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Had you done anything in high school? Were there any organizations yet?

52
00:05:52,000 --> 00:06:02,000
I didn't. I was too busy trying to pull myself up by my bootstraps. Not knowing at the time that I really didn't have any boots to put straps in.

53
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:12,000
I was going to college. I was going to be a math and PE teacher, majoring in math and minor in PE.

54
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Then I started meeting some of the students on campus who were active in the DSU.

55
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:28,000
And I met my first husband, Albert Armore. He was very active in the black student union and later became a black Panther Party member.

56
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:37,000
And that's how I got involved with the Panthers. Because I really wasn't involved in very much before then.

57
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:47,000
Are you able to go back and try to remember the first time that you became aware of the Panthers and trying to figure out what the Audiology was and what this was about?

58
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:55,000
I know he had Panthers stickers on his car. He had a little blue VW bug and when he would come to the house.

59
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:03,000
And then he would have a Mohammed speaks newspaper with him. So he was just, oh, he was getting information from everywhere.

60
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:14,000
He would come to the house and my mother would just be really, really upset. She didn't want him coming over anymore with that black Panther and that black Muslim stuff.

61
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:22,000
He took me to an anti-war protest rally, the big one that was out in Westwood.

62
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,000
And I believe it was in late 67 or summer 67.

63
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:41,000
And it just erupted and they started beating heads and stuff. And I'm standing around looking. I've never been exposed to anything like this before.

64
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:51,000
So find you that they're dragging me. Come on, we got to get out of here. So I was actually there at that rally and that was my first time saying, you know, this really isn't.

65
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:59,000
Right, I didn't watch a whole lot of TV. I was always into the books and reading and I didn't have time. So I saw that.

66
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:09,000
That was early 67 and my husband became a full fledged member of the party. He dropped out of college. I was still going to school.

67
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:17,000
He kept trying to get me to come around and do things. But I just, you know, I didn't have time for that. I had another avenue that I was going to take.

68
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:28,000
But in December 69, when the police raided all the party offices here, he was in one of the offices and they beat him up pretty badly.

69
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:36,000
He was in the hospital for a while. I broke his arm, damaged one of his eye sockets pretty badly.

70
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And then that got my attention that that woke me up. And that was in December.

71
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
And by January, I was volunteering at the local office on 44th Street.

72
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:59,000
What was left of it, you know, we still were trying to function out of there. I started doing typing for the officer of the day, type memos, form and whatnot.

73
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:09,000
And then I worked in the breakfast program. And the clinic was starting here. And I always had an interest in the body and in health.

74
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:15,000
I guess that's why I liked physical education. Other than it was just fun. I like to play.

75
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:23,000
And so I was assigned to work at the clinic and I became the coordinator, the person who ran the clinic.

76
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:29,000
That was some experience. I was 19 years old.

77
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
It's amazing how young everyone.

78
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Yes.

79
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:33,000
And what you were all took on.

80
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Yeah, yeah. But I had a lot of help from there were a lot of professionals who were willing to lend their time and talents and skills.

81
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Marie Branch was an RN and she taught at UCLA. And Terry Cooper's was a psychiatrist.

82
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And they helped us to get residents and doctors to volunteer and nursing students and nurses to come and volunteer at the clinic.

83
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
And we didn't have any paid staff there. And that's how it went.

84
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,000
These are all African American health professionals. No. No. Marie Branch is African American. Dr. Cooper's is white.

85
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:17,000
But we had an assortment of, you know, it was a real good mixture of a diversity that we had there.

86
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:24,000
Can I ask you since we're on that about other sort of coalitions that formed at that time, partners that you worked with?

87
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:37,000
There were the nurse, the student nurses, health educators. Some of the doctors who were really liberals, they had their associations that they were with.

88
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:48,000
But I was just really, really focused on running the clinic. And that was a full time job because besides caring for the community, we had to care for the party members.

89
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:56,000
And now I'm doing work with a Drew Medical School. And looking at health disparities and, you know, we're the sickest people in the world.

90
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:01,000
The community that I come from, we have, we're the sickest people in this country.

91
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:16,000
And a lot of our illnesses compare real closely to what's going on in some third world countries, in terms of our birth rate, still birth rates, low birth rate, children.

92
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And miscarriages and things like that. But I'm just saying that to say that I didn't really have time to do a whole lot of the things that was focused on running the clinic and the health of the party members.

93
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:34,000
And the people that we serve at the clinic and that that was more than a full time job.

94
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:41,000
So let's start from the beginning because you're 19 years old. You've had a year of college at this point or so. Yeah.

95
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:45,000
And are assigned this task.

96
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
It was a lot of self-study.

97
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,000
Has the clinic opened yet?

98
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:51,000
I was there to clinic open. They had a Dicks opening day.

99
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:54,000
And then you were told you'll be running this.

100
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Yeah.

101
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:57,000
And what happened?

102
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:02,000
You just get it in gear. You do a lot of self-study. You do a lot of reading.

103
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:08,000
And I said I had a lot of mentors from, especially from Marie Branch, who was the nurse and the nursing instructor.

104
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:14,000
She gave me things to read. She just taught me, I mean, she taught me how to eat yogurt.

105
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:21,000
I didn't even know what yogurt was. I'd never had yogurt when I was 19 years old. I wasn't what we ate.

106
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:32,000
You know, various uses for it. And a lot of natural healing practices we discussed as well.

107
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:38,000
I don't know. It was just you learned. You got books. You found people. We didn't have an internet.

108
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:42,000
So you had to hustle and get that information and the best that you could.

109
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And it just, I learned a lot in a little bit of time.

110
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Can you describe the physical place of the clinic?

111
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:02,000
It was a storefront. We had a lab tech student who father was a construction contractor.

112
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:07,000
So he had been working with his father for a long time. He came in and built the lab out for us.

113
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
And we were able to put up petitions so that we could have different operating rooms.

114
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:16,000
So he built out the lab and he built us a pharmacy area.

115
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:26,000
We worked with the farm. That was one of the things that the doctors did was to work with the pharmaceutical reps who came to their place and asked them to give us samples.

116
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:34,000
So that was where we got most of our medication so that we could give it to the folks who came to the clinic for free.

117
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:39,000
So we got it built out. I'm not a good judge, a square footage.

118
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:47,000
But we had three exam rooms, a little reception area, an area for the pharmacy in the lab here in Los Angeles.

119
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,000
And what was the location?

120
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:53,000
It was at 30 second and central.

121
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,000
And it was completely free.

122
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,000
Well, we had to pay rent for the building.

123
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And everything was free. We didn't charge for anything. People could get donations when they came in.

124
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:06,000
But all care was free.

125
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:13,000
So did it take some outreach to let people know that you were there and that they weren't strings attached?

126
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:22,000
Yes, yes. And we did that outreach in the community. But when folks came out to sell papers as well, you know, there was information about the clinic.

127
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:27,000
And there were articles in our newspaper about the various clinics around the country.

128
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:35,000
And we collected donations on the street for the clinic too. So folks got to learn about the clinic that way.

129
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:44,000
Do you remember any of the sort of the why we're going to do a clinic, the justification or the ideology that said that this is important?

130
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:51,000
Yes, it was one of the points of our 10 point platformer program.

131
00:14:51,000 --> 00:15:02,000
I think it's number four. We want decent health care. We want health care that, you know, keeps us healthy to start with, but gets us well when we get sick.

132
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:10,000
And so we were just carrying out our platform that we said the reason that we existed.

133
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:19,000
We knew that we had substandard housing, education, health care.

134
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:24,000
We were the most that got beat up by the police. We were going to prison more than anybody else.

135
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:32,000
So those were the things that we really were stepped out to address.

136
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:44,000
Well, I'll come back to the clinic, but I want to sort of ask about daily life of a young woman in the LH after the Panthers.

137
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:48,000
What was it like? What was the what was daily life?

138
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:55,000
I think that the young woman with a two-year-old child, well, let's see, maybe he was a year and a half.

139
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:09,000
And when I finally, after my husband got out of the hospital and I started coming around more, eventually I gave up my apartment and I just moved into the party facilities as well, me and my son.

140
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:17,000
Shortly after, I got pregnant with my daughter. That's Albert, our more the third in LH are more.

141
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:25,000
And so, when we went in the party, there were a lot of women just like me. They had children.

142
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:33,000
So we had to make provisions so that the children could be safe and care for. So we had a nursery for the children because we worked long, long hours.

143
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:40,000
We would be up in the morning in order, you know, 536 in order to get ready for the breakfast program.

144
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:46,000
So we'd get the kids fed and then folks would go off to their various work assignments.

145
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:57,000
I would go to the clinic, other folks would go to the field, other people might be working in the office where we put together our flyers, our posters.

146
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:07,000
A couple of the few of the main writers for the newspaper were from the Los Angeles chapter, so they would go to Oakland for a few days a week to work on the newspaper.

147
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:13,000
So the children had to be taken care of it, so that was first informal. So we made sure that we put that in place.

148
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:21,000
So you'd go out, strike out to the clinic about 930 or 10. You worked there to like six or so.

149
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And we often had evening clinics as well because the regular people, they have to go to work.

150
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:31,000
And so they can't take our work and say lose money. So we had lots of evening clinics.

151
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:39,000
And that's how we were able to get a number of our doctors to volunteer as well because once they got off work, they could come and volunteer their time at night.

152
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:46,000
So there were days when you may be at the clinic to 10, 10 or 11, you know, cleaning up and getting ready for the next day.

153
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:54,000
Then if you got back to the centers early enough, you ate dinner, you had political education class maybe.

154
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:03,000
And if you were on guard duty because everybody had to have a guard shift, we didn't want what was happened to Fred Hampton to happen to us.

155
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:07,000
You just didn't know. Somebody had to be watching all the time.

156
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:20,000
So we would come back from our daily assignments. And if we didn't do political education class or have some other kind of meeting or a rally or something that we needed to go to, you were lucky you might get in the bed by 12.

157
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:34,000
11 or 12. I get a couple hours sleep and you get up for your couple hours of duty to on security watch and go back to sleep and you get up and you do it all over again.

158
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:45,000
So the work ethic that we got, as such a young age, how we learned how to work like that. Nobody can outwork us these days.

159
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:51,000
And later when you go into a regular job, they just can't do it. They're not used to that kind of work.

160
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:56,000
And not saying that that's something that you should try to sustain for a lifetime.

161
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:05,000
Because it's really hard and it's wearing on your body over time. But that's what we felt that we needed to do and that's what we did.

162
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:19,000
You mentioned Fred Hampton and can you talk a little bit more about the harassment and fear and intimidation and targeting that you all experienced?

163
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:33,000
Yes, we had, we were harassed and targeted by the police but other groups that we had different ideological perspectives.

164
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:40,000
One example was one day and we did this. Everything was communal.

165
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:47,000
The laundry, everything got you. If you were assigned to do laundry, you might have four or five people's and their family, the kids laundry to do.

166
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:57,000
So my girlfriend and I were going to do laundry one evening. And as soon as we pulled out of the parking spot, they're the police.

167
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:09,000
So they just stayed right there and waited for you to drive off so that they could stop you and harass you for some petty traffic infraction that they say that you might have committed.

168
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:18,000
And so we're sitting there and one police goes to his car and then he comes back and he's got this whole portfolio of photos.

169
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:28,000
He starts asking me these people's names, people that are in the party. And then he had my license so he knew my name so he first he pulled up my husband's picture and said, who was that?

170
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:37,000
I said, oh that's my brother. So I think for the longest, without them doing any deep check and they thought that we were brother and sister eventually I think they caught on.

171
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:45,000
But I mean, every time you left, you would look to see if there was a patrol car or an unmarked car on the street.

172
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And I think the women got off a little bit easier sometime than the guys. The guys, they just knew as soon as they walked out the gate with their papers under their arm. They were going to get harassed and they were going to get arrested.

173
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:15,000
They were going to be a beat or whatever. So it was constant. And at night, especially after the raids on the various offices and all, you just, you didn't know if your number was up next.

174
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:26,000
But if you have that commitment, you stayed. People that didn't. I want to do something else with my life. I don't want to give it up this way.

175
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:31,000
Then they leave. So people came and they went. Some people stayed longer than others.

176
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:35,000
Did you have strategies for coping?

177
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:42,000
Drink it and drug it.

178
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
This might be one of the things I tell you to take out.

179
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:53,000
But no, I mean, you know, when we had a chance to cool down, if we had, we might have a party or a birthday party or something.

180
00:21:53,000 --> 00:22:00,000
It is high, high stress. It's a wonder some of us didn't stroke out or something.

181
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:12,000
No, I mean, I recognized early on that there were a lot of folks who had alcohol problems. Later on, started using different types of drugs.

182
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:19,000
But then we have to remember that these are people that came in from the community. People that joined the party, they were all doing those kinds of things.

183
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:32,000
When they came into the party, they were ready to clean up. Because it wasn't allowed. You couldn't be a drug head and alcoholic it every day and do the work that you needed to do.

184
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:41,000
So that wasn't condoned. But because we were who we were, you know, we some of us slipped back into those habits.

185
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:48,000
But no, there were, there were, we had a psychiatrist who worked with us.

186
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
Like I said, Dr. Cooper's was a psychiatrist in up north. We had a Dr. Shapiro, I think his name was.

187
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And every now and then, you know, somebody would really, you know, kind of go out there.

188
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:16,000
But for every day, having mental health services or therapy or support groups and that kind of stuff, other than just commiserating among yourselves, nothing I can recall.

189
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:30,000
What about the being a woman in the party? And I know that numerically, I think, right, sisters made up the majority at certain points.

190
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:45,000
It wasn't the easiest thing. I mean, we, based on principles, we tried to make all things equal, you know, that women could do what men could do.

191
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:53,000
And the men, you know, the men cooked the men clean, that there were men assigned to the children's centers and whatnot.

192
00:23:53,000 --> 00:24:00,000
But like I said, the people that were in the party were people who were not in the party and came into the party.

193
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:11,000
So they brought those same behaviors and, you know, some chauvinism that not just men in our community, but all over the world, the patriarchal societies.

194
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:17,000
So that was something that you, you know, constantly had to deal with.

195
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:29,000
I would think that points and was a little bit alleviated, little bit more alleviated, because eventually more and more women became, came into the leadership positions.

196
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:33,000
And it was something we had to deal with.

197
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:38,000
Is there a special bond now among the veteran Panther women?

198
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:47,000
Oh yes, yes, yes, they are there. And it's like you were in high school and you have four or five people that you bond with them.

199
00:24:47,000 --> 00:25:02,000
You don't bond with the whole class, but there are four or five of us who are, you know, still talk and commit a raid about things that are going on now and reflect on things that were going on then.

200
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:14,000
And well, a couple of us were having this discussion about how our work ethic and how, you know, we served the people body and soul was, you know, one of our slogans.

201
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:23,000
And after a while, especially when you get closer to my age, you just have to start to pull that back and say, wait, I got to take better care of myself.

202
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:35,000
I can't give all of your way every day all day anymore. I really got to reel that back and now spend more time with my grandkids and my children.

203
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:44,000
And just, yeah, we do. We have a good bond. And it's those kind of friends that probably that some people will never make in life.

204
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:50,000
These are people that you trusted your life with for real.

205
00:25:51,000 --> 00:26:04,000
How did you go back a little bit for a second, but you talked about your parents' initial reaction to your boyfriend who would later become your husband. How did they handle your involvement in the park?

206
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:16,000
My mother, well, we had a free busing the prisons program. And my oldest brother was in San Quentin.

207
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:21,000
We were here in Los Angeles, some of my mother had never been able to go and see him.

208
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:29,000
So when we had a bus trip that was going up to San Quentin, I got my mom signed up and she and I went to visit my brother in San Quentin.

209
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:43,000
And she, before that, and after that, she never went after that. It was, it was no problem. But what we were doing in the party was all right. She got an idea to, and over time, she got an idea to see some of the things that we were doing.

210
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:54,000
So she was okay with it. And my father, I think he was just more afraid for my safety. He came to accept it after point two.

211
00:26:54,000 --> 00:27:06,000
My first experience with discrimination that I can recall. My father used to take my brother and I to Texas every year.

212
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:21,000
And we would drive. And normally he lived in San Diego. We would stop in El Paso for halfway. And we would get a motel. Of course, that was like in 55, 56. So it was a black motel. You would stay at.

213
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,000
And then you would get up the next morning and get you some breakfast and drive on.

214
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:32,000
I think it's called the green book that listed African American owned motels.

215
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:37,000
I don't know. My dad just knew because he, you know, being from Texas and going back and forth all the time. Yeah.

216
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:52,000
But this one particular time we were going, I was about nine years old. We got to El Paso. And the black Baptist convention was going on. So all the black motels were taken out.

217
00:27:52,000 --> 00:28:07,000
So we had, there was no room at the end. So my dad said, I got a stop and get some sleep. So he said, I'm just going to pull over on the side of the road here. You know, we'll get a couple hours of sleep. He pulls underneath some willow trees. Well, you know how the willow trees are going.

218
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:20,000
I said, Daddy, I can't sleep. The trees are calling me. And I kept on it. Finally, he just got up and started driving. Well, it was morning. He said, I need to get some coffee.

219
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:30,000
And we need to get something to eat. Well, there everything still said no color. It's allowed and you know, whites only in black water, I mean, color water, white water.

220
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:43,000
So my dad, he said, we got a stop. He put up to the restaurant and my stepmom was saying, oh, no, Calvin, you can't go in there. You can't go in the air. He said, no, he's from Texas. He knows how to handle it. So he goes around to the back door.

221
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:54,000
And about 15 minutes, he comes back and he's got coffee and donuts and food. And so he says, I mean, that's what you have to do. You know, you just have to suck it up. You know, you and your family have to eat.

222
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:08,000
You just go and do what they tell you to do. And you come out and we get in the car and we drive on. I'll never forget that as long as I live out. That was my first introduction to, you know, I really am treated differently than other people.

223
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:18,000
Do you remember what your thoughts were and their young mind just right at that moment? Yeah. And I was wondering, you know, why why is dad have to go in the back?

224
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:27,000
And then when we actually got to my grandmother's house that year, we're passing this beautiful park with a nice woman who said, oh, and you know, Texas is humid. It's like July.

225
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:41,000
And we can go swimming there. Dad says, no, you can't swim there. But there's a black pool down the street. And we pass this beautiful high school. I said, oh, dad, is that where you went? He says, no, we go down the street.

226
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:54,000
And you can the stark differences in that park and the other park. But the thing that really got me as we were going to go to the drive in one night. So we get to the drive in movie.

227
00:29:54,000 --> 00:30:04,000
We have to go all the way in the back. The black people had to sit so far back that they had bleachers. You had to get out of your car to see the screen.

228
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:10,000
I mean, all of that in one trip. And so that that's really imprinted in my mind. I never forget that. I'll look for you about.

229
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,000
But not later.

230
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:14,000
And that was without having a big influence.

231
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Yeah.

232
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:22,000
And later on, you start to reflect back on that. But when I get back to my own community, it's the same. So you don't really think about it that much anymore.

233
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:30,000
Do you get older and start getting a little bit more consciousness about, well, there's a whole bunch of this stuff going on all the time.

234
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:34,000
And we need to do something about it.

235
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:39,000
What were some of the other survival programs that the party had in place?

236
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:40,000
I'm going to send it away.

237
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:46,000
We had a food program where we gave away free bags of food.

238
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:53,000
Rosu is to folks who were in need. This is kind of pre-food bank type of situations.

239
00:30:53,000 --> 00:31:01,000
We had a free clothing program, free coats program and the winter, especially in those places like Chicago and New York.

240
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:10,000
We got really, really cold to imagine kids having to go to school and they don't have coats to wear.

241
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,000
What else do we have? We had so many. We had a seniors program.

242
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:25,000
Seniors against the feel for an environment, it was called safe, where we would escort seniors to the bank, into the grocery store, to doctor's appointments.

243
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:32,000
In the clinics that we had outreach programs, we would actually go out into the community and do some services.

244
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:35,000
That was kind of novel.

245
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:41,000
I think we learned that from watching what they were doing in Cuba and in China.

246
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:49,000
The barefoot doctors who went out to the community to work with people to keep them well and to get them well.

247
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:56,000
Gosh, I have a whole book of what our programs were.

248
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:08,000
A legal program where we help folks who need it to find attorneys pro bono or lower rates.

249
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:18,000
We actually had people in the party who essentially were paralegals. They helped prepare for the upcoming cases and whatnot.

250
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:28,000
We had free educational programs. We had a school which was so proud of in Oakland.

251
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:35,000
Before you went to school, you went to the nursery. I'm sure that Eric will talk a lot about that.

252
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:44,000
As soon as his mom was well enough, after having the baby and strong enough, we would not have the baby go to the nursery.

253
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:52,000
Folks who were assigned to work there, they were like assigned there 24 hour on duty for the nursery.

254
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:58,000
The shifts changed week to week or however they had it set up.

255
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:09,000
But in the same with the school, when you were two and a half or so, you were potty trained and you went to the school and you started your formal education.

256
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:15,000
You go to school the day time and at night you go to the dormitory and folks who are assigned to be there.

257
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:19,000
That really freed us up to continue to work these long crazy hours.

258
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:26,000
This is how your kids pick up on Monday morning with their little bags, the van we pick them up.

259
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:30,000
They'd be at school all week and they'd drop them off on Friday night.

260
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:34,000
They're little dirty clothes and you'd clean them all up and put them back on the van on Monday.

261
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:39,000
I mean you could go and see them during the week, you know, you had time to drop in but that's it.

262
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:47,000
And they were static, they were in heaven, they were treated like little queens and kings so it was fine with them.

263
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:57,000
The hardships, some of my comrades now would tell me how angry their children were, my kids were especially my oldest boy when we left.

264
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:02,000
They were really upset that we left and we had to leave the school.

265
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,000
So I was like they're little hay then.

266
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:11,000
And so advanced, when they came out I was able to put them ahead of, a great ahead of where the schools wanted to put them.

267
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:16,000
I brought them to Los Angeles and they wanted to put them in school according to their ages and I said no, they're going to be bored in there.

268
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:22,000
So I took them to San Diego and they put them in a grade that I asked them to put them in and they've all done well.

269
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:25,000
The clinic here, what was the name of the clinic?

270
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:31,000
It was the, I'll print this Bunchy Carter people's Greek clinic.

271
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:34,000
And can you tell us who Bunchy Carter was?

272
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:35,000
Bunchy Carter.

273
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:43,000
Yeah, Bunchy Carter is the person whom he and John, as they started the Los Angeles chapter.

274
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:52,000
So in his honor and commemorating him, we named the clinic after him.

275
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:59,000
And I had the opportunity to go to a luncheon that was helpful for his mother about two months ago.

276
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:16,000
And she was like a freedom fighter from way back so I could see where he got his desire and understanding about equal justice for folks that were disenfranchised and had so many unmet needs.

277
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:27,000
His mother just, she worked in programs in starting and running civil rights type issues based programs here in Los Angeles for a long time.

278
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:28,000
A long time, yeah.

279
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:31,000
Did you ever meet him or was it?

280
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:40,000
I met, I was able to meet him one time at a rally because that was when I was just, you know, kind of coming around a little bit.

281
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:46,000
I was trying to get me to formally join and I wouldn't, but I met him at a rally once.

282
00:35:46,000 --> 00:36:03,000
And just this very impressed by the way that he carried himself and the way that he commanded the other guys to do things, and not commanded in a you do this kind of thing, but the way that he, the leadership that I saw shining out through him.

283
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:06,000
Just that one time that I met him, I was really impressed with that.

284
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:17,000
And then later on, you know, learning more about him and then reading his poetry and whatnot, you get to get a better sense of who the man really was.

285
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:30,000
What were some of the challenges, I mean, we know the circumstances of his death and different ways in which that story has been told, I suppose.

286
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:36,000
But what were some of the challenges in terms of relations with other organizations at that time?

287
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:42,000
Well, there was the, primarily the us organization, Ron Carrank's group.

288
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:49,000
And my ex-husband, Albert Amor, was at UCLA when he was going to school there when that occurred.

289
00:36:50,000 --> 00:37:01,000
And so, you know, hearing firsthand from him and one of my best friends from high school was in the party and was there at UCLA when that happened.

290
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:10,000
It just, you know, it puts us our taste in your mouth and in your heart is not right towards that bad group of folks.

291
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:14,000
Just for the record, can you, can I ask you to describe what, what happened?

292
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:24,000
My understanding is that an Eric can give you a much better account of it because she was her husband was there.

293
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:30,000
Well, it was killed with bunch of.

294
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:41,000
There was some difference in ideology about how things should be run in terms of the Black student union and what was happening with the Black students on campus and whatnot.

295
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:50,000
And, you know, the panthers, our ideology was based on what had happened in some other revolutions.

296
00:37:50,000 --> 00:38:05,000
And so, you know, we drew from, you know, from some from the Russian, some from the Chinese and some from what happened in Cuba and tried to, and things that happened in South America and in the islands and tried to put it together and make it work for what we have here.

297
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:14,000
And the dialectical materialism, what, you know, the rhetoric.

298
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:21,000
In South America, the American organization, they were very affercentrant, you know, referring everything back to Africa.

299
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:27,000
And that's not something that we did at that time, you know.

300
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:38,000
And so, just riffs occurred. Even when I was pregnant with my daughter and I was out selling papers one day, I was attacked by people from the U.S. organization.

301
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:43,000
And I was a girl with six brothers and they couldn't handle me.

302
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:53,000
And we were on the street corner so they, you know, they weren't going to try to do too much, but they did try to attack me and I was able to fend them off.

303
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:55,000
And did those kinds of things happen?

304
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:01,000
Those kinds of things happen. They would catch one or two people by themselves and, you know, people would beat them up.

305
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:07,000
And I think that that kind of stuff happened here in San Diego where us and the Panthers were there too.

306
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:14,000
Because they, I don't think that they were around in all the cities where we had chapters.

307
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:25,000
But he, I mean, and over time, you know, you, I consider myself to be someone who has some practice forgiveness and heart and whatnot.

308
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:41,000
And that one with Corangus just really hard because he did some other things after that, you know, he even, what, what did he have as his wife or some other people, other women from the U.S. organization that he was holding like captive.

309
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:46,000
And he just, and he never fessed up to what he did.

310
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:57,000
And he was convicted. And from what I recall, he was convicted. And he's still a big time professor, you know, down in San Diego and running around the country, is tossing his views or whatnot.

311
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:00,000
And I just, I can't abide.

312
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:05,000
No, I don't have hatred. I don't have enough room in my heart to be hating anybody.

313
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:11,000
But he's somebody that I don't ever have as in his presence. And I'm just fine with that.

314
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:14,000
So gunfire actually erupted that day.

315
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:16,000
Oh, oh yeah. Yeah.

316
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:23,000
And, you know, it came to head because I guess these meetings were going on and, you know, harsh words and whatnot happened.

317
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:35,000
And it's from what we believe, what I believe in a lot of other people, other people have probably had more proof than I do that Corangus gave the order for those guys to shoot, bunching John.

318
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:49,000
Because I just, and operating in collaboration with the police probably, but that's another whole issue that, you know, I don't feel like he's really cleared himself up.

319
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:55,000
And was it not long after that that the office has got rated? Or was that quite a bit later?

320
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:59,000
Yeah, that was early on in the year.

321
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:05,000
And I can remember that offices were rated in December, but that occurred earlier in a year.

322
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:09,000
I'm thinking like February and in the winter.

323
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:12,000
I remember correctly.

324
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:14,000
Yeah.

325
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:19,000
And that, that was before I was actually in the party because I didn't come along to late 69.

326
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:24,000
So, he was killed before. I came to the party.

327
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:28,000
But they were killed, weren't you in time?

328
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:30,000
Yeah.

329
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:34,000
So do you remember how people reacted?

330
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:36,000
Like I said, I was not in the party.

331
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:38,000
You were right, you were not in yet.

332
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:59,000
But what happened then, you know, it just, the carryover afterwards, it just kind of kept on the sentiments between the Panthers and us organization, got him worse.

333
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:07,000
And at that time, well, you go out and you would be collecting donations or selling papers.

334
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:14,000
And there were special corners where you would have more foot traffic and you would probably have more sales and whatnot.

335
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:16,000
One corner would be Black Panthers.

336
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:18,000
Another corner would be us organization.

337
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:21,000
One corner would be the Nation of Islam.

338
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And another corner would be the Holy Ghost Phil Christian.

339
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:28,000
Where were the Holy Ghost Christians?

340
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:30,000
They were at the airport mostly.

341
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:37,000
Yeah, so I mean it was a time.

342
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:39,000
Yeah, it was a time.

343
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:55,000
I mean, it was a very interesting period of time in the 60s and 70s just watching all the different ideas and people had about how we should be in this country.

344
00:42:55,000 --> 00:43:01,000
Now we didn't have the gang situation that we had now obviously in LA but the saucents were around.

345
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:11,000
We had gangs before the party and like I said, the community came into the party and when it came to the party, we weren't gang members anymore.

346
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:20,000
We had the slosses, the pueblos, the body snatches, we had the Roman 20s, we had a lot of gangs.

347
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:28,000
But the party attracted a lot of those folks because I mean they were out there, they had the misplaced aggression.

348
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:33,000
They were mad and upset, they knew something wasn't right but they were taking it out of the wrong folks.

349
00:43:33,000 --> 00:43:42,000
And once they got a little bit of consciousness under their belt, then they saw you know this another way for me to channel my energies.

350
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:55,000
And no, we didn't have this gang kind of situation here in LA until the party left and then the powers that we bought that dumped all the crack here and the gangs and it's...

351
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:57,000
Was there any time?

352
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:06,000
I know this from some of the other chapters where you are bringing in people from the streets who have legitimate reasons to be angry and a lot of it.

353
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:12,000
And you know when you're trying to be disciplined, right, but things spill out, was there any...

354
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:19,000
Yeah, you know, people explode, you know, but I mean you try to handle it diplomatically.

355
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:27,000
And we all know that we all came with a whole bunch of different types of baggage and you just try to deal with it case by case.

356
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:36,000
You know, so and so is... some of us are not able to go off at any time so don't go talking crazy around it especially today because such it's such happened.

357
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:43,000
I mean, you know, and over time hopefully some of those temperaments change, you know.

358
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:49,000
And some of them, they didn't, then they left, but they were asked to leave or kicked out for whatever.

359
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:51,000
And does that happen?

360
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:56,000
Yeah, people got kicked out, people got suspended, people left on their own.

361
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:04,000
So you mentioned earlier, but you so you started with the clinic here and then you got reassigned up North, right?

362
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:14,000
Yes, well actually here I was working with the finance, I mentioned that a few of the women actually went up North every year, every week to work on the newspaper.

363
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:21,000
Well the person who was in charge of finances here knew that I was pretty good with math.

364
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:27,000
And so she became my mentor, she trained me how to handle the finances as well when she was gone.

365
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:32,000
So I was doing the clinic, but I was also doing the finances.

366
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:35,000
So that's what I was doing here, both of those.

367
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:49,000
And then when there was a call for all the chapters to move up North to work in the political campaigns that we were starting, I was assigned to the George Jackson Free Clinic in Berkeley.

368
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:52,000
And became the director there.

369
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:55,000
Did you go with the whole family?

370
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:57,000
Was that when the kids were in school?

371
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:01,000
Well actually my two year old was already there.

372
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:06,000
He went when he was about two and a half, maybe close to three.

373
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:08,000
He was already up at the school.

374
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:14,000
And my daughter went with me because she was only a few months old when we moved.

375
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:22,000
So when I went there I became in charge of that clinic and it was operated pretty much the same way.

376
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:34,000
We had a lot of folks that I collaborate with there though because Berkeley is just the heart of collaboration and unity and getting things done.

377
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:46,000
We had the Berkeley Free Clinic, we had the Women's Health Collective, Haydashbury Free Clinic sent folks over to teach us about substance abuse.

378
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:48,000
So that was my first training in drug abuse.

379
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:50,000
Is that where your dad worked?

380
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:54,000
My dad and his friends, Haydashbury Clinic, we would write around the corner.

381
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:59,000
Okay, so we get a lot of help from them.

382
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:11,000
And there was an organization called Community Services United which was a coalition of nonprofits who received funding from Berkeley City.

383
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:26,000
And we met monthly to, mainly to let each other know what we were doing so that we could avoid duplication of services so that you wanted to go and ask for money, you weren't asked for money that the city was already funding something for.

384
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:35,000
And so that, yeah, there were a lot of people that we worked with and we worked with UC Berkeley had a group called the Black Health Science Caucus.

385
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:46,000
These were pre-med students who came and volunteered their time and worked in the labs and worked in the clinic and taught us how to do different lab work.

386
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:55,000
We were here in Los Angeles but more so in Berkeley, I and some of the other clinic workers were, we were taught a lot about medicine.

387
00:47:55,000 --> 00:48:03,000
We were, I tell folks, we were probably practicing medicine without a license but we had physicians there who were overseeing what we were doing.

388
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:08,000
We worked with a lot of, Vietnam vets who were corpsmen as well.

389
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:16,000
So they had a lot of on the ground skills by how do you work with folks in an emergent type situations and whatnot.

390
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:29,000
So we learned how to draw blood, we learned how to do stitches, we worked on frank voters, we worked on winters to do stitches because the skin is real sensitive and it's like real people skin.

391
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:43,000
So we did women's exams, we did vaginal exams and I have a very personal experience with that that we would practice on each other and then we would send our labs out.

392
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:50,000
So mine came back positive for cervical cancer or something irregular.

393
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:54,000
So we did it again and sent it out again, came back again.

394
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:06,000
So I went to my gynecologist and sure enough I had to have surgery but that's how I found out that I had cervical cancer and I forget that I'm a cancer survivor these days because I caught it so early.

395
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:12,000
I just never, never think in terms of being a survivor but I am and that's how I found out.

396
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:14,000
It's really fun, that's amazing.

397
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:19,000
So we, the MIRP manual, I mean it just tells you about all the different diseases and illnesses and whatnot.

398
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:26,000
We just read this stuff, you know like it was a novel or something, we just collected all this information.

399
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:33,000
Oh hey, I got one of the shelves still. I've given it to all my girls, my daughters, my granddaughters.

400
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:40,000
Yes, the women's health collective book, yeah we, and we try to teach people to take care of themselves, you know as best they could.

401
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:44,000
Don't get sick, I mean we have to worry about getting well.

402
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:58,000
As much as you can, I mean some of it's a red itary, you just have to watch out for those types of things to stay ahead of diabetes and you know watching your sugar, watching your weight and that kind of stuff so we're exercising.

403
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:01,000
So we were, we were trying to do all that.

404
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:05,000
Was that part of the party platform too to maintain personal health and...

405
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:12,000
Well, let's see, what was that one of our, well I should tell people, what, what are those who treat their bodies as, for belonged themselves?

406
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:15,000
Who was something from a mower or something?

407
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:18,000
That's why we changed it around a little bit.

408
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:23,000
But yeah, I, that, folks needed to be well, needed to be well.

409
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:29,000
And we had a, a community, a community called Disease Control Program too.

410
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:37,000
We had an outbreak of a, Shagella at one of the, one of the sites.

411
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:46,000
And we worked with the pediatricians, we had pediatricians from Children's Hospital who came and ran the pediatric clinic for some of the residents came and did that.

412
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:54,000
And we were taught, you know, that you need to separate them from other people until they're asymptomatic and then they can go back and say everybody's in the middle of a community.

413
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:58,000
You know, one person gets something and it's spread like wildfire, wildfire.

414
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:01,000
Same thing with chickenpox, two or three kids in one facility.

415
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:07,000
You know, everybody was gonna get chickenpox so they were, everybody was just confined there and do.

416
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:09,000
Bring the ones that hadn't had it yet.

417
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:13,000
Yeah, let the kids go ahead, let them get it.

418
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:21,000
And then during the time of, you know, the 60s, free love, you know, free speech, free love, flower children.

419
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:30,000
I think we probably treated more STIs, STDs at the clinic than we treated a lot, especially in Berkeley than we treated other things.

420
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:33,000
But we had control in the clinic like that.

421
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:36,000
It's, we were bringing in folks from all over the country.

422
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:40,000
So as soon as you got to town, you had to come and get your medical screen.

423
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:46,000
And you got screened for a gonorrhea, syphilis, committee, you know, whatever.

424
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:48,000
Did you have a yeast infection?

425
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:56,000
You got treated. If you had something that someone else could catch by you having sex with them, you were put on a list.

426
00:51:56,000 --> 00:52:02,000
And you were not to have, and that list was published, and you were not to have sex with anyone that was on that list.

427
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:04,000
This was within the park.

428
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:06,000
There was no hip-a-laws in the park.

429
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:12,000
But I mean, that's how you control because it was rapid.

430
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:23,000
I mean, in Berkeley, there was, in the very, there was just a lot of STDs at that time, because everybody was, you know, free love.

431
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:26,000
That's why I never heard that before.

432
00:52:26,000 --> 00:52:28,000
So we are in Berkeley.

433
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:29,000
Yes.

434
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:31,000
So how long were you all at the, or are you in the office?

435
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:32,000
I was there.

436
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:38,000
I was in the Bay Area from 72 to 77.

437
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:44,000
And I ran a clinic from 72 to about 74.

438
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:52,000
And that was by the time that Huey left the party, then Bobby left, and then Elaine became the person in charge.

439
00:52:52,000 --> 00:53:00,000
And she knew that I had the experience, the person who handled the finances here was handling, been handling the finances there.

440
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:06,000
And she knew that I had the experience from Los Angeles, so she asked me what I'd come and become the Minister of Finance.

441
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:13,000
So I left the clinic and started handling the headquarters finances.

442
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:22,000
We were there when Elaine was made president that evening or day when she was announced as the head of the department.

443
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:26,000
I probably was.

444
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:35,000
Actually, I was just recovering from surgery, so I may not have been, I was there in the area, but I may not have been at the particular event.

445
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:37,000
Like I said, I had a relapse.

446
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:47,000
And so she asked me while I was recovering, would I take over the finances, because that's one of the big shifts in personnel, I guess you call it now.

447
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:53,000
And so I told her, yes, so right that was like in late 74, I started handling the finances.

448
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:56,000
So you worked out of headquarters in Oakland, my home.

449
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:03,000
Yeah, and Oakland headquarters, but yeah, I did a lot of work from where I live as well.

450
00:54:03,000 --> 00:54:07,000
So can you tell me what that was like, especially that transition?

451
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:14,000
Yeah, well, like I said, I was just handling the finances here, so it was just on a bigger scale there.

452
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:34,000
I had to make sure that the funds were accounted for when folks came in from getting donations, selling papers, if people gave us donations, to make sure that all the properties were the notes and the rents were paid, utilities, and people had money for food.

453
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:39,000
And you know, they had the clothing if they didn't have other kinds of income.

454
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:56,000
But everyone who had some kind of income, this was one of the eat it steady, eat lane came up with everyone who had some kind of income paid a tie, whatever you got, 10% went into the pot for the very survival programs and to maintain the facilities where you lived and whatnot.

455
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:04,000
So I was responsible for making sure that the money got collected and distributed bills paid properly.

456
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:10,000
Later we were able to incorporate the school and get grants.

457
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:17,000
So then I had to learn to be an accountant, to book keeping officially before I was just keeping things in ledgers.

458
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:28,000
But I had to learn to actually do the accounting records, keep those together and bring them up to the point of trial down to then give them to the CPA to do the 990 tax returns.

459
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:34,000
And so that was my introduction into the real nonprofit world.

460
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:41,000
And so I did that from 74 to 77.

461
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:49,000
And since then I've been doing healthy finance.

462
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:56,000
So did you, a couple of questions. One is I'm just curious. So you were married.

463
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:00,000
Was it difficult to maintain a relationship during?

464
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:07,000
Yes, when I moved to Oakland, my husband was still stationed in Los Angeles.

465
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:14,000
And I was in Oakland for probably a couple of years.

466
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:17,000
And yeah, it was just strained. It was strained.

467
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:23,000
And we never really got back together until we both left the fight.

468
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:32,000
So you know, we went our separate ways and the kids, I had the kids one weekend and then he'd have them because he did eventually move there.

469
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:36,000
But he became a stripping with multiple squalsis.

470
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:40,000
And was, you know, what he could do was limited.

471
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:45,000
He actually became my assistant in the finance area because he couldn't do a lot of field work.

472
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:48,000
So we worked together very closely up there.

473
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:56,000
And even when we weren't living it, it was difficult.

474
00:56:56,000 --> 00:57:03,000
There were a number of folks that came in a couple and I don't know if any of them left that way.

475
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:11,000
But that's not to say with the high degree of divorce in our community that it wouldn't have happened anyway.

476
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:13,000
Just...

477
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:16,000
I'll talk about that later.

478
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:24,000
So can you tell me the story of leaving the party?

479
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:28,000
Yes, I will.

480
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:33,000
Huey came back from Cuba.

481
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:39,000
And as you know, things would just start to be so different.

482
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:45,000
Because when Elaine took over, we started doing more...

483
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:49,000
What do you say mainstream type of funding we got?

484
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:57,000
We even had a law enforcement grant to run some of the services that we had this school nonprofit.

485
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:08,000
Then we had a nonprofit that was like a social service wing that worked with all these other programs that clinic fell under that, the seniors program fell under that clothing.

486
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:14,000
Food, other programs outside of education fell under that social service wing.

487
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:22,000
So that we were getting into operating more legitimately as far as other people were concerned.

488
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:27,000
But it also helped to bring in monies that made our programs sustainable.

489
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:31,000
And when Huey came back, you know, things just...

490
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:35,000
They just changed. He had some different ideas.

491
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:44,000
I don't know. He maybe just been so brilliant that it was just a lot of brilliant people.

492
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:49,000
Especially those that are so forward thinking, this is my idea.

493
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:52,000
That he was so forward thinking.

494
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:55,000
And in a way, you could kind of see ahead.

495
00:58:55,000 --> 00:58:58,000
That if we kept going like this, this is where we would be.

496
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:01,000
And it would be that kind of visionary.

497
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:07,000
That could put a lot of strain on a person, especially when you're trying to get other folks to see what you see.

498
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:10,000
And we're too dumb. We're not that intelligent.

499
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:14,000
The general person can't understand it like that.

500
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:20,000
And what that does to a psyche and a mentality of a mental healthable person.

501
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:25,000
So he kind of started acting differently.

502
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:28,000
And so people started leaving.

503
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:30,000
The women started leaving.

504
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:35,000
And then when he came back, he had this charge that he left because of in the first place.

505
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:42,000
That he was supposed to shot the prostitute, I believe.

506
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:51,000
And so the witnesses, there was one witness finally, you know, finding they published her address and whatnot.

507
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:56,000
So he sends somebody out to kill this person.

508
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:59,000
And then he was putting all this stuff together in my head.

509
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:02,000
So he's not around to say that he didn't do it.

510
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:05,000
But this is me.

511
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:12,000
But when he got there, when they got there, the person, they went to the wrong house.

512
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:15,000
The lady's house, they went to, had a gun.

513
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:18,000
When they were trying to get in, she started shooting through the door.

514
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:23,000
So she shot some of the guys that came to get the witness.

515
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:26,000
And one of the guys died on the spot.

516
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:30,000
And I said, we all live communally.

517
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:36,000
So the guy that died had the same address on his license as where I was living.

518
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:41,000
So once they get his prints, then they get the search points and whatnot.

519
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:48,000
Then they come to that search, when they come to, you know, bust in my house.

520
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:51,000
Then they go search everything.

521
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:54,000
There were guns around almost all the houses.

522
01:00:54,000 --> 01:00:55,000
They belonged to the party.

523
01:00:55,000 --> 01:00:57,000
There wasn't our houses most of them.

524
01:00:57,000 --> 01:01:00,000
And most of them were our, most of them had some stuff.

525
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:02,000
But they were only parts.

526
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:07,000
I think at that time, they felt that, you know, if the barrel was here,

527
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:11,000
and the trigger housing was here, and this was someplace else,

528
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:14,000
that, you know, they couldn't put any kind of charges on you.

529
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:16,000
Well, that wasn't true.

530
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:19,000
So when they went up to this closet,

531
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:21,000
did my kids play hide and seek in?

532
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:22,000
I didn't know what it was.

533
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:26,000
They were just little suitcases, police cases in there.

534
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:29,000
They came and they just started cartoning out all kind of stuff.

535
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:32,000
I'm like, oh my goodness, I'm going to jail.

536
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
I'm going to jail.

537
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:38,000
But it was a, it was an eye-opening time.

538
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:44,000
It really was, you know, that he would order something like that, you know,

539
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:47,000
to save himself when I just stayed in Cuba.

540
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:52,000
And so, you know, that was, you know, things just started spiraling after that.

541
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:54,000
And then people started leaving more.

542
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:02,000
And I went to jail, and then I got kicked out.

543
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:05,000
Because now, QE had to fight this case.

544
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:08,000
So why spend the resources to fight my case?

545
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:12,000
If he's going to need it, resources to fight his case.

546
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:15,000
So I was on my own.

547
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:16,000
You kicked your other party?

548
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:17,000
Yeah.

549
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:18,000
Yeah.

550
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:21,000
But what I had on my back.

551
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:27,000
So I left and I fought my case for a year.

552
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:32,000
And I ended up getting sentenced to two years in California State Prison.

553
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:35,000
Which I did 12 or 13 months.

554
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:38,000
And then I went to work for a low.

555
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:41,000
And while I worked for a low,

556
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:45,000
there was this Jewish woman there to work with parolees.

557
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:49,000
But while I was in prison, that was an interesting experience, too.

558
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:54,000
I never, I didn't even have traffic tickets on my records, you know.

559
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:57,000
I went, do not pass, go, go.

560
01:02:57,000 --> 01:02:59,000
Do not collect $200, go directly.

561
01:02:59,000 --> 01:03:03,000
Because I was at the time when it was not used to go and go to jail,

562
01:03:03,000 --> 01:03:04,000
but have a gun, go to jail.

563
01:03:04,000 --> 01:03:07,000
You know how the wind shift back and forth.

564
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:09,000
And it was right during that time.

565
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:10,000
Have a gun, go to jail.

566
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:13,000
My fingerprints weren't on anything.

567
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:16,000
You know.

568
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:18,000
And so there were a couple of people in the jewelry.

569
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:20,000
We got a chance to pull them afterwards.

570
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:24,000
And a couple of them said that they really didn't believe that I had any control over it.

571
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:29,000
But that's what it would take for you to be guilty to have knowledge, possession, and control.

572
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:30,000
So it was my house.

573
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:32,000
The utilities were in my name.

574
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,000
They said, I had control of it.

575
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:36,000
But anyway.

576
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:38,000
So where were you in cursory?

577
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:43,000
Here in Frontier, California, it's two for women.

578
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:47,000
But when I went there, I stayed in the reception center for three months.

579
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:52,000
Normally they transition you in, do your physical, psych, and you're out two or three weeks.

580
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:58,000
But they were watching me making sure that I wasn't going to inside a riot or something.

581
01:03:58,000 --> 01:03:59,000
Format revolution.

582
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:02,000
Yes, yes, they should know that I was so far.

583
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:06,000
At that point in my life, I was like, that was the last thing I was thinking about.

584
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:13,000
And so when I finally moved me to the main campus, they put me in a cell by myself because they didn't want me in.

585
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:20,000
And that was right fine with me because there was some folks up there whether she would want to sell with.

586
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:27,000
I mean, because they were always doing things they would be going to jail in jail for the activities in there.

587
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:35,000
Nothing political, brewing hooch and doing whatever other kinds of things that they get you locked up while you're already locked up.

588
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:41,000
So, sitting worked circulate that you were a black man there and what did that, what kind of response did they get from?

589
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:45,000
I got a lot of respect from everybody.

590
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:50,000
The administration were giving me a hard time initially.

591
01:04:50,000 --> 01:04:55,000
But eventually I became secretary for the Women's Advisory Council.

592
01:04:55,000 --> 01:04:58,000
And I had a pass, I could go in and out administration.

593
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:00,000
I had a typewriter in my room.

594
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:02,000
I went in and wrote in college class.

595
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:04,000
I got my AA degree while I was there.

596
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:12,000
I transferred my credits from Berkeley and in Cal State LA and got an AA and took a couple other classes.

597
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:21,000
So, when I got out at work study, this woman sent me on interviews and I had four interviews and I was off of jobs by three people.

598
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:42,000
So, I went back to school, got my bachelor's in healthcare administration and kept working and then went back to the state and school and got a master's in health administration, mostly in administering substance abuse programs.

599
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:51,000
And then at the age of 55 I went back to school and got a marriage of family therapy and taking the masters.

600
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:56,000
So, you know, I just kept moving and didn't look back.

601
01:05:56,000 --> 01:06:03,000
I mean, it was something being in the party, I wouldn't have the skills to do the things that I've done since if I hadn't been there.

602
01:06:03,000 --> 01:06:12,000
That was just really unfortunate event that happened and that I had to deal with and be away from my family for that amount of time.

603
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:21,000
But, you know, it's over and you chalk it up to experience and just keep moving forward.

604
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:23,000
You're saying?

605
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:26,000
Yeah, I didn't know that I'd ever put that on film.

606
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:38,000
I wanted to ask about the other nonprofits, especially shields for families, but I don't know if that was first in the progression.

607
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:47,000
No, well, I worked with some other nonprofits here in Los Angeles.

608
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:58,000
But in 1990, I was working for the county alcohol and drug program.

609
01:06:58,000 --> 01:07:01,000
I stayed with them for about a year and a half.

610
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:04,000
I waited too long to become a government employee.

611
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:08,000
I couldn't go through the just pretending to work.

612
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:15,000
I mean, I've talked about my work and I couldn't come into work and push your paper from this side of the desk to the other side for the evening tomorrow.

613
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:19,000
I'll come in and move it over here and act like I'm doing something.

614
01:07:19,000 --> 01:07:23,000
So, my supervisor and I were, we'd be writing grants.

615
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:31,000
We'd be there late at night, we'd come in on weekends and we had over $20 million of funding to come in to support substance abuse programs.

616
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:42,000
Specifically, women's programs for women who had substance abuse problems and their children were born prenatally exposed to drugs.

617
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:53,000
We were there when Diane Watson introduced a bill into the state legislature asking to have funds set aside for the before county hospitals in Los Angeles to address that issue.

618
01:07:54,000 --> 01:08:02,000
Because at King Hospital, over 1,200 children and year were being born prenatally exposed to drugs, primarily crack.

619
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:05,000
So, the bill passed, became law.

620
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:11,000
So, the doctor who was a neonatologist at King called us at the county,

621
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:18,000
she had worked with us on the proposal and said, you know, I know how to treat the children, but I don't know how to run a drug abuse program.

622
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:20,000
You guys can have to come out and run it.

623
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:24,000
So, my boss and I left the county, came out and started running the program.

624
01:08:24,000 --> 01:08:28,000
Initially, it was under the auspices of a true medical school.

625
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:36,000
But after about a year or so, we formed our own 501C and started getting our monies directly.

626
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:43,000
We started with a grant of about a half million dollars a year, 14 employees.

627
01:08:43,000 --> 01:08:52,000
And after 24 years, when I retired, we had 350 employees in about 25 million dollars in funding.

628
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:53,000
You tell us about the first.

629
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,000
28 or 29 programs.

630
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:57,000
You tell us about the first building, in quotes.

631
01:08:57,000 --> 01:08:59,000
The first building.

632
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:10,000
We were given an old trailer that it was set on the land of Drew Medical School, but the trailer belonged to Martin Luther King Hospital, County Hospital.

633
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:17,000
In South Central, that was built by the riots, as a direct result of that.

634
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:21,000
But the building was so old and dilapidated, it should have been condemned.

635
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:25,000
It had been sitting in for a long time, and you just had to watch where you stepped.

636
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:30,000
Certain places, your foot, my God, go through to the bottom.

637
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:34,000
But we pieced it together and made it work.

638
01:09:34,000 --> 01:09:45,000
So we ran our program out of there for a while, and we're able to get funding from the Department of Health Services to help us renovate that trailer and to build us another one so that we could expand.

639
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:54,000
So we just started with a one program for women who had drug abuse problems, who had children, 0 to 5.

640
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:01,000
And they came into the program when they were pregnant or right after they had a baby that was tested positive for drugs.

641
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:04,000
And we worked with them on the substance abuse issues.

642
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:10,000
Then we started seeing that they were coming in close to homeless or homeless.

643
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:21,000
So we went out and found some apartments, got some money from HUD, put together some packaging and bought two 18-unit apartment complexes that we could house some of the women in.

644
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:24,000
And they just kept coming in homeless.

645
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:30,000
And so we found another project in Compton, 86-unit.

646
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:33,000
So we bought that so that we could house more.

647
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:35,000
And more of them were coming in with mental health issues.

648
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:37,000
So we got a psychiatrist to come and work with us.

649
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:43,000
So we started looking at the behavioral health, the other behavioral health concerns.

650
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:48,000
We were able to get funding from the Department of Mental Health to help with that.

651
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:51,000
And that more funding from the Department of Substance Abuse, where we used to work.

652
01:10:51,000 --> 01:10:54,000
And they were one of our main funders at the time.

653
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:56,000
And it still are.

654
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:04,000
Started with vocational services because most of the women maybe had a 4 to 6 great education or reading level.

655
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:06,000
So all these are so related.

656
01:11:06,000 --> 01:11:09,000
There are similar programs that we had in the party.

657
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:10,000
So the three.

658
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:17,000
And what I did at SHIELD was I was the health officer for the longest.

659
01:11:17,000 --> 01:11:23,000
We had a major AIDS grant and I was the primary person working on that.

660
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:28,000
So as well as the financial piece, I became the chief operating officer.

661
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:32,000
So I had some programmatic responsibilities from time to time.

662
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:39,000
But yes, the programs that were that and still are run out of SHIELDs.

663
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:42,000
They kind of mirror, kind of work that I did when I was in the party.

664
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:46,000
So I can't ever regret what I did.

665
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:52,000
Because it's at the stage and helped me to build the skills to do what I needed to do when I came back here.

666
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:56,000
And you worked through all these major epidemics.

667
01:11:56,000 --> 01:12:01,000
Drug epidemic, AIDS, crack, gang, but yeah.

668
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:02,000
Yeah.

669
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:06,000
And SHIELDs was very instrumental because it's in what?

670
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:10,000
We started right there on 120th in Compton.

671
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:15,000
It now has probably 17, 18 sites.

672
01:12:15,000 --> 01:12:20,000
And we're in about 20 schools doing mental health services as well.

673
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:25,000
So we're all over the South Central, Linwood Watts, Willoughbrook area.

674
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:30,000
And even down that far from here, we have a resource center.

675
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:35,000
Yeah, I've watched, I've seen a lot of things come and go.

676
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:38,000
And I've seen so much cyclical stuff happening.

677
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:42,000
Now with healthcare reform, which I'm really happy past.

678
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:46,000
We're having some unexpected consequences.

679
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:51,000
As a result of it, there's still a lot of bugs to be worked out.

680
01:12:51,000 --> 01:12:56,000
But we went from, we're now going back to what they call a medical model where

681
01:12:56,000 --> 01:13:01,000
they want substance abuse services to be treated in the medical facility.

682
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:07,000
And we thought to change that back in the 80s and 90s

683
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:11,000
and we're able to have substance abuse look at differently.

684
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:14,000
Because there are some aspects that are a lot different.

685
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:17,000
That's not to say that it couldn't be treated.

686
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:19,000
And it's good to have integrated care.

687
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:23,000
It's just really concerned that they're now going to be excluding the people

688
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:31,000
that have done this treatment services for so long and upping the requirements for them to have degrees.

689
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:34,000
And a lot of these folks are recovering people who have, you know,

690
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:37,000
they've learned certain sets of skills.

691
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:41,000
And we just don't know what's going to happen with that.

692
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:43,000
Now.

693
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:45,000
Is it difficult when you see things cycle back?

694
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:46,000
Oh, it is.

695
01:13:46,000 --> 01:13:51,000
I think about Mother May I, you know, you take two baby steps forward and ten giant steps backwards.

696
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:53,000
And you think, you know, I did all this.

697
01:13:53,000 --> 01:13:57,000
I stayed up all those long hours for what?

698
01:13:57,000 --> 01:14:03,000
Sometimes you wonder, you know, how could we have let it roll back like this again?

699
01:14:03,000 --> 01:14:08,000
But I think we'll work out that medical piece as long as Trump doesn't get elected.

700
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:13,000
We'll be able to work through some of those things.

701
01:14:13,000 --> 01:14:23,000
But I've gone, I've retired from SHIELDs, but I was asked to become part of community faculty at Drew Medical School.

702
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:29,000
Which is a different type of track of instructors.

703
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:33,000
There are people like me who have been working in the community with nonprofits,

704
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:38,000
running nonprofits for years and years.

705
01:14:38,000 --> 01:14:44,000
And what we are commissioned to do is to work with the medical students, nursing students,

706
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:48,000
MPH students, to help them to understand the community better,

707
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:52,000
help them to understand better the social determinants of health.

708
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:54,000
What a phenomenal program.

709
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:55,000
Yes.

710
01:14:55,000 --> 01:14:57,000
Are there others in the country doing this?

711
01:14:57,000 --> 01:15:01,000
No, the video only one.

712
01:15:01,000 --> 01:15:06,000
So, you know, because we think it's so important that they need to learn those skills.

713
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:10,000
It's so unfair to send the students out into the community to work in.

714
01:15:10,000 --> 01:15:14,000
Especially ones that aren't from this community, they don't know.

715
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:19,000
They don't know that just because you give this person a prescription doesn't mean they're going to take it.

716
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:23,000
First of all, it doesn't mean that they're going to buy it because they may not have the money.

717
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:27,000
They may not trust you because they keep thinking about the research

718
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:33,000
and all that kind of stuff that's happened with people of color over the years.

719
01:15:33,000 --> 01:15:41,000
So, they don't trust the medical system or they can't read what you just written and given to them.

720
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:44,000
It's just all kinds of dynamics.

721
01:15:44,000 --> 01:15:47,000
And then you go home with the family dynamics and they say,

722
01:15:47,000 --> 01:15:49,000
you know, you don't take that.

723
01:15:49,000 --> 01:15:52,000
You take these herbs and mix it with this bark and do that.

724
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:54,000
You don't take that medicine.

725
01:15:54,000 --> 01:15:57,000
So, it's all these other social determinants of health that, you know,

726
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:01,000
the students have to be trained on.

727
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:06,000
And even the existing, the current professors, it's a hard thing because a lot of the old guys,

728
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:09,000
they're not trying to change what they're thinking.

729
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:15,000
So, when you go and try to teach the students and they get in the classroom and they tell them what they've always told them.

730
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:21,000
And I keep saying we got to think of a different way to do something because obviously what we're doing is not working

731
01:16:21,000 --> 01:16:24,000
because my people still die in the illness.

732
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:29,000
Something's not working somewhere so we need to tweak this a little bit.

733
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:33,000
But to turn to those who've actually been working in the trenches,

734
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:35,000
there's so much sense.

735
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:39,000
Yeah, so it's been interesting and I've been able to

736
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:42,000
follow us under the auspices of UCLA.

737
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:48,000
So, I work with some doctors and nurses there, especially in the research department.

738
01:16:48,000 --> 01:16:55,000
And I've been working on some of the committees to look at diversity in the medical education curriculum.

739
01:16:55,000 --> 01:17:02,000
And how do we train the physicians and how do we train the existing instructors?

740
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:08,000
How do we train the students about some of these concepts that, you know,

741
01:17:08,000 --> 01:17:13,000
do you think that they need to know about working in our communities?

742
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:15,000
So, that's what you're doing now?

743
01:17:15,000 --> 01:17:17,000
Yeah, I do that a little bit.

744
01:17:17,000 --> 01:17:23,000
Yeah, so don't tell them some advice we've got for diabetes and stroke prevention and things like that.

745
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:25,000
But more health-related things now.

746
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:28,000
When I heard you retire, I didn't think that that would last long.

747
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:31,000
I guess a how do you retire from a passion?

748
01:17:31,000 --> 01:17:35,000
I keep trying, you know, I'm learning to say no more.

749
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:42,000
I haven't learned to say no all the time yet, but I'm going to get there one day.

750
01:17:42,000 --> 01:17:51,000
Coming back to the Panthers for a moment, what are your thoughts about how the Panthers are remembered or thought of?

751
01:17:51,000 --> 01:17:56,000
You know, and this is, again, like working with kids and what people know.

752
01:17:56,000 --> 01:18:00,000
I'm curious what your thoughts are on.

753
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:03,000
Things that I think that I'd like to see them.

754
01:18:03,000 --> 01:18:10,000
Yeah, you know, or ways in which you think, you know, maybe the Panthers are misremembered or misrepresented,

755
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:13,000
or what you would like kids to know.

756
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:15,000
Okay.

757
01:18:15,000 --> 01:18:28,000
Well, the whole piece about the guns and self-defense, I mean, that that, that's important.

758
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:31,000
I mean, because if you're dead, all the rest of this doesn't count.

759
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:33,000
There's no need to look at anything else.

760
01:18:33,000 --> 01:18:36,000
So we have to make sure that we're safe first.

761
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:39,000
But that wasn't the hype.

762
01:18:39,000 --> 01:18:43,000
That wasn't the ultimate of what the party was about.

763
01:18:43,000 --> 01:18:47,000
We had a plethora of survival programs.

764
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:52,000
And we called it survival-pending revolution because we knew it would be a long protracted struggle

765
01:18:52,000 --> 01:19:00,000
before we got to see any of the changes made that we knew needed to occur in order for us to,

766
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:03,000
to our people to start living a better life.

767
01:19:03,000 --> 01:19:07,000
And when I say our people, I'm talking about all poor and oppressed people in this country and the world,

768
01:19:07,000 --> 01:19:13,000
because the United States, you know, they had their tentacles all over the place.

769
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:21,000
But I'd like to know that the party was interested in children and adults

770
01:19:21,000 --> 01:19:28,000
in every facet of our lives to make sure that we had the best life possible.

771
01:19:28,000 --> 01:19:35,000
And we did what we could to make that happen for as long as we could do it.

772
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:41,000
So anything that I didn't ask that I should have asked?

773
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:47,000
I don't think so.

774
01:19:47,000 --> 01:19:49,000
I don't think so.

775
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:56,000
And just my children, you know, it's interesting that children have a different take on things.

776
01:19:56,000 --> 01:20:06,000
And my daughter, she's right out there, she's an educator, but she's really for making sure that the children of color get what they need

777
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:14,000
and runs into a lot of obstacles in the educational systems because of that.

778
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:20,000
But what she remembers most about the party was that the camaraderie,

779
01:20:20,000 --> 01:20:24,000
and she still has friends that she still collaborates with.

780
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:29,000
And when she left, she was only about, maybe she was six or seven years old.

781
01:20:29,000 --> 01:20:32,000
But she grew up in it, yeah.

782
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:38,000
And she still in touch with those people and those are like lifelong friends forever.

783
01:20:38,000 --> 01:20:43,000
But yeah, I just like the young people to know that, you know,

784
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:47,000
I like for them not to make some of the mistakes that we made.

785
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:55,000
To be open to hear our stories, to see where we step in the ditch so that they don't have to step in that same ditch,

786
01:20:55,000 --> 01:21:01,000
they can move around it and go higher and farther than we did.

787
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:09,000
I just think of one thing I wanted to ask you, we talked a little bit before we started the camera about working with other like-minded organizations,

788
01:21:09,000 --> 01:21:17,000
especially the Brown Berets. Could you talk a little bit about what those kind of coalition buildings are?

789
01:21:17,000 --> 01:21:32,000
Yes, I can remember working in some of their rallies and just coalescing with them in activities and events that they were having.

790
01:21:32,000 --> 01:21:42,000
And having similar ideologies and I can remember some of our party members going out working with Susan Chavez and the farm workers.

791
01:21:42,000 --> 01:21:53,000
And just forming coalitions with, you know, who was ever open to talk about, let's make some changes in this country because we know if we can make them here,

792
01:21:53,000 --> 01:22:00,000
hopefully they don't be able to extend out through the rest of the world where people are oppressed like they are here.

793
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:07,000
So like I said, I was mostly focused on the health piece, I didn't get a chance to be out more.

794
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:17,000
And at that time more people in the top leadership were doing that. I didn't really become in the party's executive committee until I became the finance minister in Oakland.

795
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:21,000
So a lot had happened before I got to that point.

796
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:34,000
Yeah, but there was a lot of coalescing going on with the great panthers and with the seniors in the universities.

797
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:44,000
And anti-war movement, the women's movement? Yes, yes, all of those.

798
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:47,000
Fellas, any questions?

799
01:22:47,000 --> 01:22:52,000
No, I just want to talk about that. Coaching up in water?

800
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:55,000
Happy sale. I guess I didn't have one question.

801
01:22:55,000 --> 01:23:06,000
You mentioned talking to young people saying once you could tell them that might be mystified some of the sort of unfortunate and prelicious method of panthers.

802
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:12,000
In your own mind, what, looking back on it for years ago, you walked in that door at the time of the party?

803
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:17,000
Did you ever see that trajectory taking you to where it was now?

804
01:23:17,000 --> 01:23:26,000
I did not. I did not see myself as a visionary. I guess I still don't make in summary guards that I might be.

805
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:37,000
But I was more a day-to-day grinder, get the work done, make sure the books are okay, make sure the hell is okay.

806
01:23:37,000 --> 01:23:47,000
I guess maybe is it my left side of my brain is just totally taxed and I haven't really exercised to write very much.

807
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:53,000
I'm trying to do more of that now and stepping out and thinking about different things that might occur.

808
01:23:53,000 --> 01:24:01,000
But I never felt like I really had the time to allow myself to let my mind go there.

809
01:24:01,000 --> 01:24:08,000
It was like, okay, here I am today. And then you go three or four years and you look like you say, my goodness, how did I get here?

810
01:24:08,000 --> 01:24:11,000
I didn't expect to be at this point.

811
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:16,000
A lot of times you didn't even know you were going to be alive the next year.

812
01:24:16,000 --> 01:24:22,000
So that kept a lot of us, I think, from thinking ahead like that.

813
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:35,000
But to be thinking that I would come out of the party, especially after being in prison and being able to keep moving ahead and moving up and still being able to do the same types of work on a broader scale.

814
01:24:35,000 --> 01:24:42,000
As I came back to this community, it's just not something that everyone crossed my mind.

815
01:24:42,000 --> 01:24:48,000
But I'm glad that I had that experience and skills to be able to come and do that.

816
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:54,000
But we're grateful to you for the work that you've done and for sharing your story today.

817
01:24:54,000 --> 01:24:57,000
Thank you for involving me.

818
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:01,000
Absolutely. Thank you.

819
01:25:01,000 --> 01:25:03,000
Okay.

820
01:25:03,000 --> 01:25:12,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

